@flexiarg peripherals/surface-earns-inhabitation
@title Surface Earns Inhabitation
@sigils [🏠/居]
@audience peripheral designers, surface builders, agent architects
@tone foundational
@style pattern
@keywords surface, peripheral, inhabitation, friction, UX, interface, trust, adoption, CLI, REPL, usability
@references [agent/scope-before-action agent/evidence-over-assertion peripherals/constrained-execution-envelope peripherals/inhabitation-feeds-evolution futon-theory/mission-lifecycle equity/shared-maintenance coordination/par-as-obligation]

! conclusion: A productive interface that nobody uses is dead infrastructure; the surface must earn inhabitation by being less friction than the alternative.
  + context: You have built a peripheral or surface with genuine capabilities —
    evidence logging, frame persistence, coordination, structured tool visibility —
    that the primitive alternative (a CLI, a one-shot API call, an ad hoc script)
    lacks.
  + IF:
    The surface offers real infrastructure advantages over the primitive path, and
    you want agents or humans to actually inhabit it rather than bypass it.
  + HOWEVER:
    The surface is cluttered, difficult to enter, or tedious to operate. Basic
    operations that work effortlessly in the primitive path (interrupt, inspect,
    navigate) are broken or awkward. The inhabitant spends their energy fighting
    the interface rather than doing the work the interface was built to support.
    So they don't use it. They reach for the primitive path because it has less
    friction, even though it has less capability.
  + THEN:
    Treat surface usability as load-bearing infrastructure, not cosmetic polish.
    Close every friction gap between the surface and the primitive alternative
    before adding new capabilities. The surface must be strictly better at the
    basics — responsiveness, interruptibility, visibility, stability — so that
    inhabitation is the natural choice, not a discipline exercise.
    Concretely:
    - Every operation the primitive path supports must work at least as well.
    - The surface's unique capabilities (evidence, frames, coordination) come
      free with inhabitation, not as extra steps.
    - If the inhabitant has to fight the surface, the surface is broken, not
      the inhabitant.
  + BECAUSE:
    Uninhabited infrastructure is dead infrastructure. The value of a peripheral
    is not what it *can* do but what it *does* do — and it does nothing if nobody
    is inside it. I-3 says peripherals are inhabited, not delegated. But
    inhabitation is not commanded; it is earned. The surface earns it by being
    the path of least resistance to productive work.
    This applies symmetrically to agents and humans. An agent that bypasses the
    proof peripheral to one-shot tool calls, and a human who bypasses the REPL
    to type in a terminal, are exhibiting the same behavior for the same reason:
    the primitive path has less friction. The fix is the same in both cases —
    not to block the primitive path, but to make the infrastructure path
    frictionless enough that it becomes the natural choice.
    + evidence: M-repl-wins-over-cli (futon3c, 2026-03-29): the Claude REPL had
      evidence logging, frame persistence, agent coordination, and structured
      tool visibility — but interrupt didn't kill the server process, tool calls
      showed only opaque markers, streaming text hijacked the cursor, and port
      discovery was fragile. The CLI had none of the capabilities but all of the
      basics. Joe reached for Alacritty every time. Fixing the basics (interrupt,
      tool detail, cursor stability) was not UI polish — it was the work that
      made the infrastructure inhabitable.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Building capabilities before basics: the surface can do amazing things but
      can't be interrupted, so nobody trusts it with long-running work.
    - Treating UX as separate from architecture: "we'll polish the UI later"
      means the UI never gets polished because the architecture was designed
      without considering the inhabitant's experience.
    - Blocking the primitive path instead of earning preference: disabling the
      CLI doesn't make the REPL better; it just makes the user resentful.
    - Confusing feature count with inhabitability: adding more capabilities to
      an already-cluttered surface makes it worse, not better.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Audit every surface for friction gaps against its primitive alternative.
    - Prioritize closing friction gaps over adding new capabilities.
    - Measure inhabitation (do agents/humans actually use the surface?) not
      capability (could they theoretically use it?).
    - Apply the same standard to agent-facing surfaces (peripherals) and
      human-facing surfaces (REPLs, dashboards, inspectors).
